---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navigation from "../../components/Navigation.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Getting Started with Arduino: A Beginner's Guide"
  description="Learn the basics of Arduino programming and start building your first electronic projects today!"
>
  <Navigation />

  <main class="flex-1">
    <!-- Article Header -->
    <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-16">
      <div class="mb-8">
        <a
          href="/blog"
          class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 font-medium inline-flex items-center mb-6"
        >
          ‚Üê Back to Blog
        </a>
        <div class="flex items-center space-x-4 mb-4">
          <span
            class="px-4 py-2 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full text-sm font-semibold"
            >Electronics</span
          >
          <span class="text-gray-500">8 min read</span>
          <span class="text-gray-500">March 15, 2025</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
          Getting Started with Arduino: A Beginner's Guide
        </h1>
        <div class="flex items-center space-x-4">
          <div
            class="w-12 h-12 bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-500 to-purple-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold"
          >
            SC
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Sarah Chen</div>
            <div class="text-sm text-gray-500">Electronics Enthusiast</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Featured Image -->
      <img
        src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1553406830-ef2513450d76?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop"
        alt="Arduino Board"
        class="w-full rounded-2xl shadow-2xl mb-12"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
      />

      <!-- Article Content -->
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Arduino has revolutionized the world of electronics and DIY projects,
          making it accessible for beginners and experts alike. Whether you're
          looking to build your first LED circuit or create complex IoT devices,
          Arduino is the perfect starting point.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">
          What is Arduino?
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Arduino is an open-source electronics platform based on easy-to-use
          hardware and software. It consists of a physical programmable circuit
          board (microcontroller) and a piece of software, or IDE (Integrated
          Development Environment) that runs on your computer.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">
          Why Choose Arduino?
        </h2>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-3 mb-6">
          <li>
            <strong>Beginner-Friendly:</strong> Simple, clear programming language
            based on C++
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Affordable:</strong> Arduino boards start at just $20-30
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Versatile:</strong> Can control lights, motors, sensors, and
            more
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Community Support:</strong> Massive online community with thousands
            of tutorials
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Open Source:</strong> Free software and open hardware design
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">
          What You'll Need
        </h2>
        <div class="bg-blue-50 p-6 rounded-xl mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
            Starter Kit Essentials:
          </h3>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2">
            <li>Arduino Uno board (or compatible)</li>
            <li>USB cable (usually included)</li>
            <li>Breadboard for prototyping</li>
            <li>Jumper wires</li>
            <li>LEDs (various colors)</li>
            <li>Resistors (220Œ© and 10kŒ©)</li>
            <li>Push buttons</li>
            <li>Sensors (temperature, light, motion)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">
          Setting Up Your Arduino IDE
        </h2>
        <ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-3 mb-6">
          <li>Download the Arduino IDE from arduino.cc</li>
          <li>Install the software on your computer</li>
          <li>Connect your Arduino board via USB</li>
          <li>Select your board type under Tools ‚Üí Board</li>
          <li>Select the correct port under Tools ‚Üí Port</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">
          Your First Program: Blink LED
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Let's start with the classic "Hello World" of Arduino - making an LED
          blink!
        </p>
        <div
          class="bg-gray-900 text-gray-100 p-6 rounded-xl mb-6 overflow-x-auto"
        >
          <pre><code class="text-sm">{`void setup() {
  pinMode(LED_BUILTIN, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  digitalWrite(LED_BUILTIN, HIGH);  // Turn LED on
  delay(1000);                      // Wait 1 second
  digitalWrite(LED_BUILTIN, LOW);   // Turn LED off
  delay(1000);                      // Wait 1 second
}`}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">
          Understanding the Code
        </h2>
        <ul class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 mb-6">
          <li>
            <strong>setup():</strong> Runs once when the Arduino starts. Used to
            initialize settings.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>loop():</strong> Runs continuously after setup(). Your main program
            logic goes here.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>pinMode():</strong> Configures a pin as INPUT or OUTPUT.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>digitalWrite():</strong> Sets a pin HIGH (on) or LOW (off).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>delay():</strong> Pauses the program for specified milliseconds.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Next Steps</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Once you've mastered the basics, try these projects:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-3 mb-6">
          <li>Create a traffic light system with multiple LEDs</li>
          <li>Build a temperature monitor with an LCD display</li>
          <li>Make a motion-activated alarm with a PIR sensor</li>
          <li>Control motors to build a simple robot</li>
          <li>Connect to WiFi and create IoT projects</li>
        </ul>

        <div
          class="bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-600 to-purple-600 text-white p-8 rounded-2xl mt-12"
        >
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">üí° Pro Tips for Success</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-3">
            <li>‚úì Start simple and gradually increase complexity</li>
            <li>‚úì Always check your wiring before powering on</li>
            <li>‚úì Use the Serial Monitor for debugging</li>
            <li>‚úì Join Arduino forums and communities for help</li>
            <li>‚úì Document your projects and share them!</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Conclusion</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Arduino opens up a world of possibilities for makers and tinkerers.
          With just a basic kit and some creativity, you can build amazing
          projects that combine hardware and software. The key is to start
          simple, learn from examples, and don't be afraid to experiment!
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
          Happy making, and welcome to the wonderful world of Arduino! Share
          your projects with our community and inspire others to start their
          maker journey.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Share Section -->
      <div class="mt-12 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Share this article</h3>
        <div class="flex space-x-4">
          <button
            class="px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-blue-700 transition-colors"
          >
            Share on Twitter
          </button>
          <button
            class="px-4 py-2 bg-blue-800 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-blue-900 transition-colors"
          >
            Share on Facebook
          </button>
          <button
            class="px-4 py-2 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-red-700 transition-colors"
          >
            Share on Pinterest
          </button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Related Posts -->
      <div class="mt-16">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <a
            href="/blog/building-first-robot"
            class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-lg p-6 hover:shadow-xl transition-shadow"
          >
            <span class="text-sm text-purple-600 font-semibold">Robotics</span>
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-2">
              Building Your First Robot
            </h4>
          </a>
          <a
            href="/blog/smart-home-raspberry-pi"
            class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-lg p-6 hover:shadow-xl transition-shadow"
          >
            <span class="text-sm text-purple-600 font-semibold"
              >Raspberry Pi</span
            >
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-2">
              Smart Home Automation
            </h4>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
